videoData.title: Doctors make mistakes. Can we talk about that?
videoData.socialTitle: Doctors make mistakes. Can we talk about that?

recommendations.blurb: Must-reads (and a must-watch) about the realities of medical mistakes.

recItems.blurb: *Medical Errors and Medical Narcissism* examines the concept of medical narcissism and how error disclosure to patients and families is often compromised by the health professional's need to preserve his or her self-esteem – at the cost of honoring the patient's right to the unvarnished truth about what has happened. This book is essential reading to unpack the hidden personality issues that lead to error and get in the way of making meaningful changes to health care safety.
recItems.headline: Medical Errors and Medical Narcissism
recItems.label: READ_BOOK

recItems.blurb: *The Checklist Manifesto* is Gawande's bestselling book about medical errors that come from not knowing enough and errors that come from not doing the right thing.  The book is essential reading for people who want to understand why health care is not as safe as it could be and how to change that.
recItems.headline: The Checklist Manifesto
recItems.label: READ_BOOK

recItems.blurb: The inspirational *New York Times* bestselling autobiography of a true American hero. In *Highest Duty*, Captain Chesley 'Sully' Sullenberger — the pilot who miraculously landed a crippled US Airways Flight 1549 in New York’s Hudson River, saving the lives of all 155 passengers — shares his thoughts on leadership and responsibility. Sully believes that health care needs to adopt the same approaches that made aviation safer. I, for one, agree wholeheartedly with him.
recItems.headline: Highest Duty
recItems.label: READ_BOOK
recItems.note:
Chesley Sullenberger and Jeffrey Zaslow
William Morrow, 2009

recItems.blurb: An article adapted from my address to the graduating medical school class at the University of Toronto in June 2014.
recItems.headline: Canada's Doctors: The Best, the Brightest — and the Burned Out
recItems.label: READ_ARTICLE
recItems.note:
Brian Goldman
*The Globe and Mail*, June 16, 2014

recItems.blurb: Grumet's TED-style talk is a marvelous reflection on medical mistakes and personal traumas that shape a doctor's demeanor and capacity for empathy.
recItems.headline: Jordan Grumet
recItems.label: WATCH

nodes.whoTheyAre: Brian Goldman is an emergency-room physician in Toronto, and the host of CBC Radio’s "White Coat, Black Art."
nodes.whyListen: Brian Goldman is an emergency room physician who has worked at Mount Sinai Hospital in downtown Toronto for more than 20 years. He is also a prominent medical journalist and the host of CBC Radio’s White Coat, Black Art. In Dr. Goldman’s first book, The Night Shift, published in 2010, he shares his experiences of working through the witching hours at Mount Sinai, as well as at the other hospitals where he has spent his long career.

videoData.description: Every doctor makes mistakes. But, says physician Brian Goldman, medicine's culture of denial (and shame) keeps doctors from ever talking about those mistakes, or using them to learn and improve. Telling stories from his own long practice, he calls on doctors to start talking about being wrong.
videoData.socialDescription: Every doctor makes mistakes. But, says physician Brian Goldman, medicine's culture of denial (and shame) keeps doctors from ever talking about those mistakes, or using them to learn and improve.
